PROVENANCE: Provenience Description - Under IC/7E (stake) In lower shell-clearing Grave 2. Section number - 7E Trench Number - IC Human remains date - Late Archaic Moorehead Phase Locality - Bluehill Falls, Me.
PUBNOTES: Note with object reads 'These are in fill and not with burial.' See field notes, pp. 900-911.
UDF21: Feature description - This grave was recorded in the field. The human remains of an infant (1-2 yrs) of indeterminate sex are not extant. The grave contained funerary objects. Object association notes - 'The shells were broken and mixed with humus--the proportion of humus increasing with depth. This was undoubtedly the grave shaft, but notes do not reflect that it was ever outlined. A large and small plummet, a piece of incised bone and a fragment of celt in this supposed fill were not considered as grave goods....Two metapodial awls, made from bones split transversely and their distal ends shaved in the same plane to form broad flat tips, lay over the right arm with their proximal ends on the thin remnants of the frontal and parietal bones and their tips on the left arm. Two sharply pointed bone implements with a pronounced curve lay over the left arm. The bone from which they had been made could not be identified. About 15mm from the proximal ends of each were encircling shallow marks that could be vestiges of a wrapping or handle. Parallel to the left arm were two foreshafts for male harpoons, made of swordfish sword. One was made of a sword without cells, the other from a sword with cells that had been exposed when the sword was split. Diagonal lines about 2mm wide had been cut through the skin of the latter at irregular intervals. Below the foreshafts lay what proved to be a human [unclear as of 6/1995-LR] humerus, probably the left, from which the head (the proximal end) had been cut and the distal articular processes had been trimmed. A transverse hole had been drilled at the upper end of this implement--probably made from a left humerus. A single-barbed male harpoon with a gouged line hole lay near the northeast limit of the grave close by a small hammerstone and a decomposed piece of iron pyrite. From among the leg bones came a sliver of bone cut from a larger piece, possibly a needle in the first stage, with burrs of bone still attached. Pieces of curled birch bark were found in red ochre at the east end of the grave and at its northwest side.' (Byers, 1979: 38-39) Excavator's remarks - 'Grave 2 (Fig. 17) contained the remains of a baby, with head to west....It was at first assumed to be a cache of bone tools, but the cache proved to be the burial of a young child placed on the surface on which the midden accumulated--a layer of compacted loam resting on a till surface that was sufficiently uneven to cause knobs of till to overlay the basal layer. The grave lay in the pebbles and loam in which there were scraps of refuse bone. It seems probable that this layer once marked a living surface.' (Byers, 1979: 38) General remarks - The burial was very well defined by red ochre and retained a high degree of integrity. Notes and catalogs show few conflicts. Funerary object NAGPRA status - UFO?
REPATNOTES: Association with Grave 2 unlikely. Feature Consultation notes - Human remains were not recovered from the field; it is unclear whether the above mentioned humerus is human. If it is human, the objects below are considered associated, if not there are no other extant human remains with which objects are associated. (LR 3/96)

A large and small plummet, a piece of incised bone and a fragment of celt in this supposed fill were not considered as grave goods....Two metapodial awls, made from bones split transversely and their distal ends shaved in the same plane to form broad flat tips, lay over the right arm with their proximal ends on the thin remnants of the frontal and parietal bones and their tips on the left arm. Two sharply pointed bone implements with a pronounced curve lay over the left arm. The bone from which they had been made could not be identified. About 15mm from the proximal ends of each were encircling shallow marks that could be vestiges of a wrapping or handle. Parallel to the left arm were two foreshafts for male harpoons, made of swordfish sword. One was made of a sword without cells, the other from a sword with cells that had been exposed when the sword was split. Diagonal lines about 2mm wide had been cut through the skin of the latter at irregular intervals. Below the foreshafts lay what proved to be a human [unclear as of 6/1995-LR] humerus, probably the left, from which the head (the proximal end) had been cut and the distal articular processes had been trimmed. A transverse hole had been drilled at the upper end of this implement--probably made from a left humerus. A single-barbed male harpoon with a gouged line hole lay near the northeast limit of the grave close by a small hammerstone and a decomposed piece of iron pyrite. From among the leg bones came a sliver of bone cut from a larger piece, possibly a needle in the first stage, with burrs of bone still attached. Pieces of curled birch bark were found in red ochre at the east end of the grave and at its northwest side.' (Byers, 1979: 38-39) Excavator's remarks - 'Grave 2 (Fig. 17) contained the remains of a baby, with head to west....It was at first assumed to be a cache of bone tools, but the cache proved to be the burial of a young child placed on the surface on which the midden accumulated--a layer of compacted loam resting on a till surface that was sufficiently uneven to cause knobs of till to overlay the basal layer. The grave lay in the pebbles and loam in which there were scraps of refuse bone. It seems probable that this layer once marked a living surface.' (Byers, 1979: 38) General remarks - The burial was very well defined by red ochre and retained a high degree of integrity. Notes and catalogs show few conflicts. Funerary object NAGPRA status - UFO?
REPATNOTES: Association with Grave 2 unlikely. Feature Consultation notes - Human remains were not recovered from the field; it is unclear whether the above mentioned humerus is human. If it is human, the objects below are considered associated, if not there are no other extant human remains with which objects are associated. (LR 3/96)

PROVENANCE: Provenience Description - Grave pit 1. Level Overflow: 'The level into which it was dug remains in doubt.' (Byers, 1979:28) Human remains date - Late Archaic Moorehead Phase Excav Date - 1936
PUBNOTES: Field notes, 889-899. Byers, Douglas. _The Nevin Shellheap Burials and Observations_. Papers of the Robert S. Peabody Foundation for Archaeology, vol. 9, (Andover, MA: Andover Press), 1979.
UDF21: Feature description - This grave contained the human remains of an adult male individual and funerary objects. Object association notes - 'Burial gifts included many broken bone tools and a beaming tool made from the cannon bone of a moose; the latter was placed between the knees....Other artifacts found in the grave include a trimmed beaver incisor, a small barbed point with two blunt barbs on one edge, and a fragment of a bone needle. Grave 1 was liberally sprinkled with red ochre; it covered the skeleton and the tools so that everything was deeply stained.' (Byers, 1979: 32) 'Included in the midden was a slate point with a square tang in which notches were rubbed and fragments of other slate points. A plummet and a fragment of an 'adz blank' shown with the grave may have been in the midden (Fig. 12.).' (Byers, 1979: 28) Excavator's remarks - 'Grave 1 was a flexed burial of an old adult male, lying on the left side, head west, face north (Fig.12). Although the the burial seemed closely associated with a hearth complex, there was no evidence that this was a burial beneath a hearth. Ash beds and many lenses of pebbles were noted, but none seemed to have been cut by the grave. The soil from the grave pit could be identified outside the burial feature for the pile was not completely used in refilling the grave. Although the pit just touched the IC.1 and IC.2 lines, it does not appear on the profile of either. The level from which the pit intruded included many small deposits of fish bones and scales.' (Byers, 1979: 28) General remarks - Fragments of an adult male found outside the grave boundaries may be from the adult individual in this grave. (LR, 3/96) The Peabody Museum of Archaeology and Ethnology (PMAE) at Harvard University, Cambridge, MA, is in control of the human remains from this excavation. Funerary object NAGPRA status - AFO
LEVEL: 'The level into which it was dug remains in doubt.' (Byers, 1979:28)
REPATCLAIM: Repatriated to The Wabanaki Repatriation Committee: Aroostook Band of Micmac; Houlton Band of Maliseet Indians; Passamaquoddy Tribe; Penobscot Nation.

(Byers, 1979: 32) 'Included in the midden was a slate point with a square tang in which notches were rubbed and fragments of other slate points. (Byers, 1979: 28) Excavator's remarks - 'Grave 1 was a flexed burial of an old adult male, lying on the left side, head west, face north (Fig.12). Although the the burial seemed closely associated with a hearth complex, there was no evidence that this was a burial beneath a hearth. Ash beds and many lenses of pebbles were noted, but none seemed to have been cut by the grave. The soil from the grave pit could be identified outside the burial feature for the pile was not completely used in refilling the grave. Although the pit just touched the IC.1 and IC.2 lines, it does not appear on the profile of either. The level from which the pit intruded included many small deposits of fish bones and scales.' (Byers, 1979: 28) General remarks - Fragments of an adult male found outside the grave boundaries may be from the adult individual in this grave. ORIGIN: United States | ME | Hancock | Blue Hill
PROVENANCE: Human remains date - Late Archaic Moorehead Phase Site No. - Me. 152/1 Locality - Bluehill Falls, Me. Situation - Grave 2.
UDF21: Feature description - This grave was recorded in the field. The human remains of an infant (1-2 yrs) of indeterminate sex are not extant. The grave contained funerary objects. Object association notes - 'The shells were broken and mixed with humus--the proportion of humus increasing with depth. This was undoubtedly the grave shaft, but notes do not reflect that it was ever outlined. A large and small plummet, a piece of incised bone and a fragment of celt in this supposed fill were not considered as grave goods....Two metapodial awls, made from bones split transversely and their distal ends shaved in the same plane to form broad flat tips, lay over the right arm with their proximal ends on the thin remnants of the frontal and parietal bones and their tips on the left arm. Two sharply pointed bone implements with a pronounced curve lay over the left arm. The bone from which they had been made could not be identified. About 15mm from the proximal ends of each were encircling shallow marks that could be vestiges of a wrapping or handle. Parallel to the left arm were two foreshafts for male harpoons, made of swordfish sword. One was made of a sword without cells, the other from a sword with cells that had been exposed when the sword was split. Diagonal lines about 2mm wide had been cut through the skin of the latter at irregular intervals. Below the foreshafts lay what proved to be a human [unclear as of 6/1995-LR] humerus, probably the left, from which the head (the proximal end) had been cut and the distal articular processes had been trimmed. A transverse hole had been drilled at the upper end of this implement--probably made from a left humerus. A single-barbed male harpoon with a gouged line hole lay near the northeast limit of the grave close by a small hammerstone and a decomposed piece of iron pyrite. From among the leg bones came a sliver of bone cut from a larger piece, possibly a needle in the first stage, with burrs of bone still attached. Pieces of curled birch bark were found in red ochre at the east end of the grave and at its northwest side.' (Byers, 1979: 38-39) Excavator's remarks - 'Grave 2 (Fig. 17) contained the remains of a baby, with head to west....It was at first assumed to be a cache of bone tools, but the cache proved to be the burial of a young child placed on the surface on which the midden accumulated--a layer of compacted loam resting on a till surface that was sufficiently uneven to cause knobs of till to overlay the basal layer. The grave lay in the pebbles and loam in which there were scraps of refuse bone. It seems probable that this layer once marked a living surface.' (Byers, 1979: 38) General remarks - The burial was very well defined by red ochre and retained a high degree of integrity. Notes and catalogs show few conflicts. Funerary object NAGPRA status - UFO?
REPATCLAIM: Repatriated to The Wabanaki Repatriation Committee: Aroostook Band of Micmac; Houlton Band of Maliseet Indians; Passamaquoddy Tribe; Penobscot Nation.

PROVENANCE: Level Overflow: 'The level into which it was dug remains in doubt.' (Byers, 1979:28) Human remains date - Late Archaic Moorehead Phase Locality-Bluehill Falls, ME Site No - Me.152/1 Situation-Grave pit 1.
UDF21: Feature description - This grave contained the human remains of an adult male individual and funerary objects. Object association notes - 'Burial gifts included many broken bone tools and a beaming tool made from the cannon bone of a moose; the latter was placed between the knees....Other artifacts found in the grave include a trimmed beaver incisor, a small barbed point with two blunt barbs on one edge, and a fragment of a bone needle. Grave 1 was liberally sprinkled with red ochre; it covered the skeleton and the tools so that everything was deeply stained.' (Byers, 1979: 32) 'Included in the midden was a slate point with a square tang in which notches were rubbed and fragments of other slate points. A plummet and a fragment of an 'adz blank' shown with the grave may have been in the midden (Fig. 12.).' (Byers, 1979: 28) Excavator's remarks - 'Grave 1 was a flexed burial of an old adult male, lying on the left side, head west, face north (Fig.12). Although the the burial seemed closely associated with a hearth complex, there was no evidence that this was a burial beneath a hearth. Ash beds and many lenses of pebbles were noted, but none seemed to have been cut by the grave. The soil from the grave pit could be identified outside the burial feature for the pile was not completely used in refilling the grave. Although the pit just touched the IC.1 and IC.2 lines, it does not appear on the profile of either. The level from which the pit intruded included many small deposits of fish bones and scales.' (Byers, 1979: 28) General remarks - Fragments of an adult male found outside the grave boundaries may be from the adult individual in this grave. (LR, 3/96) The Peabody Museum of Archaeology and Ethnology (PMAE) at Harvard University, Cambridge, MA, is in control of the human remains from this excavation. Funerary object NAGPRA status - AFO
LEVEL: 'The level into which it was dug remains in doubt.' (Byers, 1979:28)

Object association notes - 'Burial gifts included many broken bone tools and a beaming tool made from the cannon bone of a moose; the latter was placed between the knees....Other artifacts found in the grave include a trimmed beaver incisor, a small barbed point with two blunt barbs on one edge, and a fragment of a bone needle. Grave 1 was liberally sprinkled with red ochre; it covered the skeleton and the tools so that everything was deeply stained.' (Byers, 1979: 32) 'Included in the midden was a slate point with a square tang in which notches were rubbed and fragments of other slate points. A plummet and a fragment of an 'adz blank' shown with the grave may have been in the midden (Fig. 12.).' (Byers, 1979: 28) Excavator's remarks - 'Grave 1 was a flexed burial of an old adult male, lying on the left side, head west, face north (Fig.12). Although the the burial seemed closely associated with a hearth complex, there was no evidence that this was a burial beneath a hearth. Ash beds and many lenses of pebbles were noted, but none seemed to have been cut by the grave. The soil from the grave pit could be identified outside the burial feature for the pile was not completely used in refilling the grave. Although the pit just touched the IC.1 and IC.2 lines, it does not appear on the profile of either. The level from which the pit intruded included many small deposits of fish bones and scales.' (Byers, 1979: 28) General remarks - Fragments of an adult male found outside the grave boundaries may be from the adult individual in this grave. (LR, 3/96) The Peabody Museum of Archaeology and Ethnology (PMAE) at Harvard University, Cambridge, MA, is in control of the human remains from this excavation. Funerary object NAGPRA status - AFO
LEVEL: 'The level into which it was dug remains in doubt.' (Byers, 1979:28)
